  <static seed="563" source="PCC-ORCCA-ed3/BasicAlgebra/QuadraticEquations/solveQuad175.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>{3x^{2}+4x-8}= 0</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="29" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{\frac{-2-2\sqrt{7}}{3},\frac{-2+2\sqrt{7}}{3}\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>This equation does 
not easily factor, so we will use the Quadratic Formula:</p>
<p><m>\begin{aligned}
            x \amp  = \frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\\
                   \amp  = \frac{-4\pm\sqrt{16 + 96}}{6}\\
                   \amp  = \frac{-4\pm\sqrt{112}}{6}\\
                   \amp  = \frac{-4\pm4\sqrt{7}}{6}\\
        \end{aligned}</m></p>
<p>So <m>{\left\{\frac{-2-2\sqrt{7}}{3},\frac{-2+2\sqrt{7}}{3}\right\}}</m>.</p>
<p>Note that <em>all</em> quadratic equations have <alert>two</alert> (possibly repeated) solutions; in this problem both solutions are real. Each solution can be checked by substituting it into the original equation- this is left as an exercise.</p>
</solution>
